Q1. What is the difference between VALUE TYPE and REFERENCE TYPE?
    WHY ASKED: Almost every interviewer asks this first.

A:  "Value types (struct, enum) are copied when assigned.
    Reference types (class) share the same memory reference.

    struct Point { var x: Int }
    var a = Point(x: 5)
    var b = a       // b is a COPY
    b.x = 10
    print(a.x)      // still 5

    In iOS, most Swift standard types (String, Array, Int)
    are value types (struct). This avoids unintended side effects.

    In my apps, I use structs for data models like prayer times
    and calorie entries — because I want clean, independent copies
    when passing data between screens."

---

Q2. What is PROTOCOL ORIENTED PROGRAMMING (POP) in Swift?
    WHY ASKED: Apple uses POP heavily — top trending question.

A:  "Protocol Oriented Programming means designing your app
    around protocols (behaviors) rather than base classes.

    Benefits:
    - Works with both struct and class (unlike inheritance)
    - Multiple protocol conformance (vs single inheritance)
    - Easier to test with mock objects

    protocol Calculable {
        func calculate() -> Double
    }

    struct ZakatCalculator: Calculable {
        func calculate() -> Double { return assets * 0.025 }
    }

    In my Azaan Pro app, I used protocols to define common
    behaviors like prayer time calculation and notification
    scheduling — making each module independently testable."

