Q18. What is CLEAN ARCHITECTURE in iOS?
     WHY ASKED: Senior/lead roles ask this — shows you think big picture.

A:  "Clean Architecture separates app into layers:

    Presentation → Domain → Data

    - Presentation: Views + ViewModels (UI layer)
    - Domain      : Use Cases + Entities (business rules)
    - Data        : Repositories + API/DB (data sources)

    Key principle: Inner layers know NOTHING about outer layers.
    Domain layer has zero import UIKit — it's pure Swift.

    Example for prayer times feature:
    Entity: PrayerTime (pure Swift model)
    UseCase: FetchPrayerTimesUseCase (business logic)
    Repository: PrayerRepository (protocol)
    DataSource: FirebasePrayerDataSource (implementation)

    This means I can switch from Firebase to CoreData
    without touching business logic at all.
    I am currently refactoring Azaan Pro to Clean Architecture
    for better testability and scalability."

---

Q19. What is DEPENDENCY INJECTION and why is it important?
     WHY ASKED: Testability question — asked in all serious companies.

A:  "Dependency Injection means providing an object's
    dependencies from outside rather than creating them inside.

    BAD — tightly coupled, untestable:
    class PrayerViewModel {
        let service = FirebaseService() // hardcoded dependency
    }

    GOOD — loosely coupled, testable:
    class PrayerViewModel {
        let service: PrayerServiceProtocol
        init(service: PrayerServiceProtocol) {
            self.service = service // injected from outside
        }
    }

    // Production:
    PrayerViewModel(service: FirebaseService())
    // Testing:
    PrayerViewModel(service: MockPrayerService())

    This is how I structure my ViewModels — making it
    easy to write unit tests by injecting mock services."

---

Q20. What is COORDINATOR PATTERN in iOS?
     WHY ASKED: Navigation management — asked in mid/senior roles.

A:  "Coordinator pattern moves navigation logic OUT of
    ViewControllers into dedicated Coordinator classes.

    Problem without Coordinator:
    ViewController knows about and creates other ViewControllers
    — tightly coupled, hard to reuse.

    With Coordinator:
    protocol Coordinator {
        func start()
        func navigateToDetail(prayer: Prayer)
    }

    class PrayerCoordinator: Coordinator {
        var navigationController: UINavigationController
        func start() { show(PrayerListVC()) }
        func navigateToDetail(prayer: Prayer) {
            show(PrayerDetailVC(prayer: prayer))
        }
    }

    Benefits:
    - ViewControllers become reusable (zero navigation code)
    - Deep links easy to implement
    - Flow logic in one place

    I am familiar with this pattern and have implemented
    it in larger feature modules of my projects."

